Testing "Incremental" - the kick ass pipeline for optimising Stacks parameters!¶

How to use this notebook¶

If you are unfamiliar with jupyter notebooks - they will change your life :)

All code cells are executable. And they can be code cells or markdown cells (like this one).

The "cell magic" below means that all plots will be plotted inline in the notebook (default is to open a new window for each plot, which is annoying).

Hopefully I have explained everything well as I go through, but if not just ask. In theory, for the analyses all you need to do, is change the paths to the data and you should be able to recreate the results that I got here.

I am using Stacks v 1.35, the pipeline worked on v 1.30 but I think there is now a version 1.44, so perhaps best to start testing on that.

In [21]:
%matplotlib inline

The Test Data:¶

From Dan's PhD thesis.

The data includes 3 species of carp, the crucian carp Carassius carassius, the goldfish Carassius auratusand hybrids between them.

I have sort of randomly chosen a few individuals here, but they will be enough to show you how the pipeline works. I will put some thought into which comparisons to use in the paper when the pipeline is further along.

I will send you a link to the raw sequence files . . .

Setting up Incremental:¶

At the moment, Incremental is split into 3 modules. Each module is in its own script file. All you need to do is:

1. download scripts from here: https://github.com/DanJeffries/Incremental or clone the repo to get scripts and data all at once. 
2. Add the path to those scripts to your PYTHONPATH, as below ...
In [10]:
import sys

sys.path.append("path/containing/Incremental/scripts/")

Then you can just import them as with any other module

In [11]:
import Incremental_U as IncU 
import Incremental_C as IncC
import Incremental_Pop_mod as IncPop

Stacks parameter tests --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------¶

1. Ustacks tests - Using Incremental_U¶

Ustacks is the first module in the de-novo pipeline of Stacks. Its function is to cluster reads, based on their sequence similarity, into alleles and loci. This process is highly parameterised. So far, Incremental_U supports tests of three of the major parameters:

M: Maximum distance (in nucleotides) allowed between stacks (Stacks default 2).
m: Minimum depth of coverage required to create a stack (Stacks default 3).
MS: (--max_locus_stacks) maximum number of stacks at a single de novo locus (Stacks default 3).
In [2]:
### Fastq files are here:
Incrememntal_test_directory = "/home/djeffrie/Data/Incremental/raw_data/"  ## Note - stupidly fails if not missing the last "/" from path! Need to fix that . . .
In [7]:
## INPUT INCREMENTAL PARAMETERS HERE --( Can be in a parameter file for Cline version )----------------------

parameters = ["M", "m", "MS"]                                   ## List, eg ["M", "m", "MS"]. If only testing 1 param, this must still be a list e.g. ["M"]
M_vals =   [2,3,4,5,6]                                          ## List, eg [1,2,3,4]
m_vals =   [2,3,4,5,6]                                          ## List, eg [1,2,3,4]
MS_vals =  [2,3,4]                                              ## List, eg [1,2,3,4]
threads =  7                                                    ## Int. eg 7
parent_dir = Incrememntal_test_directory                        ## Absolute Dir containing the demultiplexed raw read fasta/fastq files
run_cline_switch =  1                                           ## to switch on (1) to run stacks cline or off (0) to run pipeline on existing Stacks outputs


## Making input dictionary --------------------------------------

Setup_dict = {}
Setup_dict["parameters"] = {}
Setup_dict["threads"] = threads
Setup_dict["parent_directory"] = parent_dir
Setup_dict["run_cline_switch"] = run_cline_switch
Setup_dict["verbose"] = False

for param in parameters:
    if "M" in param:
        Setup_dict["parameters"][param] = M_vals
    if "m" in param:
        Setup_dict["parameters"][param] = m_vals
    if "MS" in param:
        Setup_dict["parameters"][param] = MS_vals

#pp = pprint.PrettyPrinter(indent=2)
#pp.pprint(Setup_dict)

Incremental_U_outputs = IncU.IncreMental_U(Setup_dict)

There is now an intermediate step before we can proceed to the Cstacks tests:¶

Cstacks requires Ustacks outputs as its inputs. Obviously which Ustacks outputs we use will affect the Cstacks results. This is perhaps not a really big deal as the inputs for Cstacks will always be the same for all Cstacks tests - so the patterns across the Cstacks parameter values should be roughly the same regardless of the Ustacks inputs used. However, it would be good to allow the user to control this if they want.

For running the pipeline module by module separately, it is easy, we include a function (which I think I already have) to run Ustacks a final time for whatever parameter values the user likes.

But if we want to add an automated wrapper for the whole Incremental pipeline, we need to deal with this another way.

I think we could design the pipeline to run in two ways:

1. Automatic - The user defines all test parameter values and all default values for each module (Ustacks, Cstacks and Populations) in a single parameter file. Then, at the end of each step the final run of that model is run using the default parameter values or a set of specified values specifically for the final run.
2. Modular - The user runs the pipeline one module at a time, and manually runs the final commands for each module using a function that we include.

Example of 1.

User fills out parameters for all modules at start, including defaults:

Ustacks
- M_test = [2,3,4,5,6]
- m_test = [2,4,6,8]
- MS_test = None

- M_default = 2
- m_default = 4
- MS_default = 2

- M_final = 2
- m_final = 6
- MS_final = 2

Cstacks
- n_test = [2,3,4,5,6]

- n_default = 2

Populations
- p_test = [4,6,8,10]
- r_test = [0.7, 0.75, 0.8, 0.85, 0.9, 1]

- p_default = 4
- r_test = 0.75

So here, the Automatic pipeline will first run Incremental_U. For ecah of the test parameters (in this example we are not testing MS). So for Ustacks will by run for the following parameter values:

-M = 2 (test) -m = 4 (default) -MS = 2 (default)

-M = 3 (test) -m = 4 (default) -MS = 2 (default)

-M = 4 (test) -m = 4 (default) -MS = 2 (default)

-M = 5 (test) -m = 4 (default) -MS = 2 (default)

-M = 6 (test) -m = 4 (default) -MS = 2 (default)

-M = 2 (default) -m = 2 (test) -MS = 2 (default)

-M = 2 (default) -m = 4 (test) -MS = 2 (default)

etc . . . . you get the idea.

At the end of these tests, a final Ustacks run will be performed (or we can use outputs already generated if that combination happened to be included in the test parameters) usng these parameters:

-M = 2 (final) -m = 6 (final) -MS = 2 (final)

These Final Ustacks outputs will then be used for the Cstacks tests.

To run the pipeline in a modular way continue as below . . .

2. Cstacks tests - using Incremental _C¶

Here, I will just use outputs from the M = 2, m = 3, MS = 2 run from the Incremental_U run above. (I mannually moved the files into the Cstacks test directory as below).

cp /home/djeffrie/Data/Incremental/Incremental_U/*/M_tests/M_2/*tsv.gz /home/djeffrie/Data/Incremental/Incremental_C/

One slightly annoying thing about the Incremental_C module (as it is now) is that it needs the 'Sample IDs' used in Stacks. You then give Incremental_C the IDs of the samples that you want to include in the test. **NOTE that the Cstacks step is by far the longest - its not easily parrallelisable so it is best to choose a few individuals at a time for these tests.

So here's a function (in the Incremental_C module) for finding the IDs. At some point I think we could incorporate this into the pipeline so the user just gives sample names, not IDs.

In [10]:
## INPUT INCREMENTAL_C PARAMETERS HERE -----------------------------------------

To do:¶

1. Important - at the moment Incremental_C puts outputs into the same directory as the sample files. However, if you run it multiple times from the same directory for example, using multiple combinations of samples, it will overide the outputs of previous runs. So we need to structure the output directories properly.

We need to make another decision here. . . .¶

The Cstacks step is quite long - the more samples you use, the more loci are added to the catalog. The more loci in the catalog, the more time it takes to search further samples against that catalog. Thus computation time of this step can increase exponentially as more samples are added. Further more, it only possible to construct venn diagrams for 4 subsets of data - any higher and it becomes geometrically impossible to make a 2D plot of all overlaps. So I find that it is best at this stage to choose subsets of the dataset to test.

For example, as in the test data - the dataset may contain different species and hybrids. I would therefore run Incremental_C several times for different combinations of 3 or 4 samples at a time, comparing conspecifics in one run and comparing individuals from separate species, and potentially their hybrids in anoter run. This keeps computation time down, and informativeness up.

So in the automatic version of Incremental - I propose that the default is to randomly choose 3 sets of test samples, each with a different combination of individuals in the test data. We can however, allow the user to specify combinations of samples to test in this step in the parameter file.

Thoughts welcome here!

As an interesting test case, the 3 sample comparison above uses one pure C. carassius sample, one pure C. auratus sample and one F1 hybrid. You can see in the Venn diagrams how the hybrid contains more loci than either of the other two, and that many loci are shared just by the hybrid, and one of the parental species, but not the other. This is indicative of null alleles, where a Restriction site has been lost (or gained) in one of the parental species. The hybrid therefore inherits one allele containing a RAD site and one allele lacking a RAD site, meaning that it is essentially hemizygous at this locus. Although you can't see it in this step, these loci are likely to look almost entirely homozygous in the hybrid, and of course only half the coverage of the normal loci, as only one allele is being sequenced. This is a good example of how these tests can be informative for complex datasets.

I will probably try to include something like this in the paper (I am thinking somewhere like Mol.Ecol. resources would be good).

Another intermediate step now.¶

The next step in the Stacks pipeline is to use the Sstacks module to search all individuals (using Ustacks inputs) against the catalog made with Cstacks.

There are no parameters here that are worth testing, so this step can just be run as usual in order to produce the outputs required for the final module, Populations.

For the automatic pipeline, before this step we will need to run the Cstacks step properly for all the samples before it can be used for the Sstacks step. So again I propose a similar system as in Incremental_U - the defualt parameters are used for the final Cstacks run, unless the user specifies final Cstacks parameters in the parameter file.

Once this has run, the Sstacks stage can be run automatically without any input from the user. And then we can move on to the Populations module of Stacks using Incremental_Pop.

Populations tests - using Incremental_Pop¶

The Populations module of Stacks does a lot. It takes all of the outputs from the previous three Stacks modules, collects genotype and haplotype information for a set of specified samples and can output that information into a number of different formats. It also performs lots of population genetics analyses.

So far, Incremental deals with 3 parameters:

p: minimum number of populations a locus must be present in to process a locus.
r: minimum percentage of individuals in a population required to process a locus for that population.
m: specify a minimum stack depth required for individuals at a locus.

So to get the catalog including all samples using Cstacks, I am just running the Incremental_C module with all samples and only one n value.

And now running Incremental_Pop¶

Analysis_parameters1["p_default"] = 2 ## The value of p when other params are being tested. Set as 2 for males and females!
Analysis_parameters1["r_vals"] = [0.75, 0.85, 0.9, 0.95]
Analysis_parameters1["r_default"] = 0.75 ## The value of r when other params are being tested. 
Analysis_parameters1["m_vals"] = [2,3,4,5,6]
Analysis_parameters1["m_default"] = 3 ## The value of m when other params are being tested.

Analysis_parameters1["run_cline_switch"] = 1 ## run command line or not.

Let me know what you think about the graphs outputted by Incremental_Pop. The box plots look weird here, because so few samples were used. I would normally run IncPop on many more samples, as this step is quite short computationally. As I mentioned, I would like to add another plot which includes heterozygosity vs coverage. And maybe some more based on the Fstats if useful.

Again, we can include IncPop in the automated pipeline, but I really prefer to run it separately, as its very difficult to get an idea of the effect of the data filters (p, r) on just a small subset of the data. So in the automated pipeline, perhaps we can have a switch string for example. The pipeline might be run like this

Incremental(parameter_dict, "110") ## for within python

or

python Incremental.py --parameters /path/to/param/file.txt --switch 110 ## for command line.

where the switch string "110" would mean run Incremental_U and Incremental_C but not Incremental_Pop and the string "100" would run just Incremental_U.
